04776nam a22007095i 9781442687868DE-B159720200623100627.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200623t20202009onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426878687 a10.3138/97814426878682doi  a(DE-B1597)551102  a(OCoLC)1100698361  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aB785.L33bD513 2009eb 7aPHI0050002bisacsh04a128/.462221 aEbreo, Leone, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDialogues of Love /cLeone Ebreo; Rosella Pescatori. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2009  a1 online resource (464 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tIntroduction: The Dialogues of Love of Leone Ebreo -- tIntroduction -- t1. On Love and Desire -- t2. On the Universality of Love -- t3. On the Origin of Love -- tAfterword: The Dialogues of Love in Spanish -- tNOTES -- tPRINTED EDITIONS AND TRANSLATIONS OF THE DIALOGHI D'AMORE -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX OF BIBLICAL AND MYTHOLOGICAL-ASTROLOGICAL NAMES -- tINDEX OF NAMES AND WORKS 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFirst published in Rome in 1535,Leone Ebreo's Dialogues of Love is one of the most important texts of the European Renaissance. Well known in the Italian academies of the sixteenth century, its popularity quickly spread throughout Europe, with numerous reprintings and translations into French, Latin Spanish, and Hebrew. It attracted a diverse audience that included noblemen, courtesans, artists, poets, intellectuals, and philosophers. More than just a bestseller, the work exerted a deep influence over the centuries on figures as diverse as Giordano Bruno, John Donne, Miguelde Cervantes, and Baruch Spinoza.Leone's Dialogues consists of three conversations - 'On Love and Desire,' 'On the Universality of Love,' and 'Onthe Origin of Love' - that take place over a period of three subsequent days.They are organized in a dialogic format, much like a theatrical representation, of a conversation between a man, Philo, who plays the role of the lover andteacher, and a woman, Sophia, the beloved and pupil. The discussion covers a wide range of topics that have as their common denominator the idea of Love. Through the dialogue, the author explores many different points of view and complex philosophical ideas. Grounded in a distinctly Jewish tradition, and drawing on Neoplatonic philosophical structures and Arabic sources, the work offers a useful compendium of classical and contemporary thought, yet was not incompatible with Christian doctrine. Despite the unfinished state and somewhat controversial, enigmatic nature of Ebreo's famous text, it remains one of the most significant and influential works in the history of Western thought. This new, expertly translated and annotated English edition takes into account the latest scholarship and provides aninvaluable resource for today's readers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aDialogues. 0aLovevEarly works to 1800. 0aLovexEarly works to 1800. 0aLovexPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh1 aBacich, Damian1 aPescatori, Rosella, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978144268786840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781442687868423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442687868.jpg  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA